segments.text: Interview with Mr. D.A.
Anderson, Side 2.
I ran across a plan that I thought was very innovative when we were on the council, and that was a plan to anchor Mr. Miller's plan.
Yeah, I'm very proud of that.
When I look around and see all of these trees growing that are about 30 feet tall today, and there's several up and down this street.
And I selected the seed from the trees at the East Cape and had them planted out at the sewer plant.
Well, some of them were down at the cemetery as well.
And then offered them to the citizens to plant.
And it was obvious at that time because you could go around and there were no trees in front of the home.
And this was an opportunity to provide the trees free.
And now some of them told me that live oak would take all, you know,
Years and years to grow.
But all you have to do is look around the parks today.
You know, there are two trees across the street that I brought in from my neighbor.
Look at the trees around the cemetery and around the parks and put them around.
I feel a little proud when I ride around.
They're from acorns that I collected on the campus.
I guess it was at the same place, but we didn't know.
Yeah.
And did you plan to move to Stafford?
Yeah, that's right.
They were about two or three feet tall.
And then a certain day, we made them available.
And we had some city people out there to dig them up.
And I think the company started out
I think they use, I don't know what they use, I forgot.
But we made them available and quite a few of the trees even went to brine.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
But I'm sorry that they didn't keep up that program because I, oh, I make, you know, I had a heart attack and I make a daily walk of one mile at least.
And, of course, I look at all the trees and, you know,

uh some some of these places could still stand a few permanent good permanent trees yeah around the park up here at thomas park and around the cemetery we put some you know that as you win the cemetery make the rounds and use usually light old trees favorite from the trees and the area then was a lot
less tree populated, I guess, is the best way to put it.
Well, it was here, right.
It was fairly rare?
Well, yeah, when I first came.
Well, now that was later though.
But people have tried to put in some trees right along.
But a lot of the, you know, there were no trees.
And they were building homes out in open spaces and no trees around.
And here was an opportunity to put out some small saplings.
Today, they're a nice-sized family.
Well, I think making the city look, the appearance of the city, making it look like it's very important for the residents to create that atmosphere.
So I thought that was a, you know, interesting story.
What happened to it?
Did it stop?
It stopped after I got out.
We, you know, the suit came along, a lot of things.
We couldn't hardly do much under the suit.
We were in the court down here, the county court.
We won down here under Judge Davis.
Then they dragged us over to the court in Austin and we were over there.
There's another long story there I could tell too someday.
But some parties are still living.
I think that something like this is ideal.
Now, a lot of people will buy trees.
Some people do not know how to buy trees, and they use the wrong trees in the wrong place.
And I see people still planting sycamore or planting cottonwood.
Well, that's the worst thing in the world they can do.
And they really need some advice.
I think the city made a fuss when they were fixing this parking area here, too, and attempted to save the trees.
Well, all the trees died.
I could have told them that had they come to me.
I would have told them they would die and why.
But no, whoever plotted or planted that parking space, I can understand.
They sure didn't seek advice.
Well, they put, you know, there was a huge pine tree.
They tried to save it.
And all the rest of the other trees there, you know, they made new islands around it.
Well, they were going to die.
I knew that.
A pine, number one, a pine needs an acid site, acid soil.
That's why pine trees do not grow here naturally.
They grow in East Texas where the soil is acid.
And any pine tree that is planted here produces twice the tendency to produce its own acid through the deposition of needles and things of this nature.
But then you come along with that lime and spread that lime all over and spray that lime all over the tree.
You go and cut, sever the roots.
And I just cringed when I saw what they were doing.
And I'm knowing what was going to happen.
And why they didn't come to somebody or go.
Why didn't they go to the people they had that knew something about trees?
I get upset when I go around walking around here and see the type of trees people are still planting.
And why they don't, intelligent people, why do they plant a tree in a certain location?
We wouldn't want to plant a live oak
You want heat or sun in the winter around here.
You don't want to be shielded by a big old light on a tree that will make part of your house cold during the winter.
You know, little things.
Well, that's something else.
I haven't told them about getting my thoughts on this yet.
I haven't seen Gary.
I chatted and corresponded with him here not too long ago about another matter.
I want to see him about that.
Yeah.
Yeah, I know.
Who burned it?
No, that was a friend of mine.
I say friend.
He's a colored friend.
Oh, I see.
And he said it to integrate the schools.
I was wondering if it was something he asked today.
They were having a discussion.
No, I will not tell you who.
Oh, yeah.
But I know, and he did it to me with a big laugh.
But he burned it in order to integrate the schools.
And that was the first parks or recreation area that I tried to establish for the Negro community.
I had what I called a mayor's committee made up of black people in the community.
There were, I think, about nine from every segment of the city then, and with the different churches represented.
You've got to study that thing so that there would be, you know, this cross-section balance.
We met right here.
And at first, they were reluctant to say anything to me.
You know, even though a lot of them knew me, they just didn't know what.
So about the third meeting, they began to open up.
And how...
the city could help them and what we could do with our financial resources and the like.
Now, the Lincoln, or not the Lincoln, but the street.
Going all the way down.
Not Lincoln?
Lincoln, Lincoln, Lincoln.
Lincoln was one of the streets that they wanted in for that neighborhood over there.
And the county road, the extension of the county road to the Wilbur Road was one over here.
And we discussed that here and how that would help to get them out of the mud over there and do things over there.
We also got in to such things as
Let's see, housing, 238 housing, 328.
Yeah, for the put-in houses.
We discussed that.
And then there was a, I forget his name.
We had an area then over in the south side, I forget what street that was on, where we started to build houses.
under the HUD program for a very reasonable cost.
And the group that sat around here thought that would be a good idea and that that would get some people out of their present homes and such good homes.
Well, they built.
I haven't been over there lately.
It seemed to me they built around 5,000 or 6,000.
And I encourage them.
I mean, it was program 235 or 238.
This was my attempt to help the colored people.
But they never took to it.
For some reason, they never wanted to move into the rain after these homes were built.
And that program went downhill, you know, fast.
And then we had a meeting following, well, I wanted to know why on things like this.
Then they brought out the matter of most of them, where they worked, and the low salary and monthly rate.
And I said, well, with your help, I'd like to make a survey of all the Negro people in College Station.
And I'll need your help, because without it, it wouldn't be any good at all.
And they agreed.
And we surveyed every Negro home in the community.
They did.
And they guaranteed me that this was an accurate survey that never had one been done so completely.
And I knew where each one worked, like in the shoe factory or university, wherever they worked, number of children.
Everything, every facet.
in this survey, and then I put it all together, and several enlightening things came out of the survey.
We met here and discussed them.
Those were working for the university.
Some of them were also at the really low end of the scale on a knowledge basis.
Some had worked 15 years for the university and still had no benefits.
They had nothing.
So then I took this survey.
Now, that's in the city.
I only wished I had kept it private.
I took the survey then and went to, I think it was Rudder.
I think it was Rudder.
And related to him some of the problems that we had in the city in terms of the colored people and their treatment at the hands of the university.
And within a year, Rudder had done quite a bit in getting them on a permanent, you know, like instead of $2.40 an hour, $3 an hour, they would be making $300 a month.
And then, but they'd get hospitalization and sickness, you know what I mean, the things that this makes.
Now, no one knows this, but I worked hard.
and getting this for the colored people in the community, all based on that survey.
And then we finally worked through the Lincoln Street and the County Road, extension of County Road.
Then we came to the Lincoln Center.
This was another project.
And I mentioned the burning.
We got into burning.
But I went ahead.
And they told me that they'd do what they could.
So we made that into a parks building, you know, for recreation.
And I've never had so many frustrations in my life.
You know, the kids over there would throw rocks and break the windows and tear down the doors.
And I'd almost cry.
And I said, now, fella, I can't go to my city council and get
them to approve the maintenance of that building just continually.
I said, I'm trying to do it.
And I know you fellas are.
And they were trying, Steve.
So I said, something has to be done.
Otherwise, we'll just have to give up on it.
And I even went so far as to arrange for the purchase of some land behind that at that time.
It was another lot.
I think it was a lot, yeah.
So then we met over there at the community center and brought in some other local people.
And of course they were there, you know, just to listen, so to speak.
And I explained to the whole group over there what our problem was and that I was trying to do it for them.
And, you know, it was a place where their kids could go.
And I needed their help, and unless I could get it, well, we'd just have to give it up.
And they got up, and, hey, Anderson, we pledge to you, we do this and that.
And they did.
After a while, they took care of the kids that were doing all that stuff.
And most of the Negro community today, at least the old people,
You ask them about me, and I'll tell you, you won't have any, they'll do anything for you.
Oh.
Well, I was curious, had a committee for the Negro people been established before?
Oh, no, no.
I started it.
Why did you decide to start it?
Oh, I started all the committee idea myself.
That was during my regime.
We never had all these committees.
Okay.
No, the only one we had was the cemetery committee.
But beyond that, that was really the, the planning zone.
But the other committees I instituted because I saw need of traffic safety and these others.
And so this, that was my idea.
Well, why would they continue if they don't have a debate in here?
Do you know why?
Well, you have to, it was my committee, you might say, because I could, I had rapport
You know, it got to the point where they'd call me up at night and say, well, Mayor Anderson, there's a fella from Houston over here at the Green Lantern, you know, over on the other side.
And he's here to cause trouble.
And he'd even describe him sometimes.
So I'd call the police, and the police would go over there and get him and take him out.
In other words, where they'd begin to help me and help themselves, too.
Yeah, I know, but it wasn't then.
Oh, and my heart bled because, you know, people would criticize me, well, you're just like a nigger.
I mean, what are you trying to do?
And I was doing everything I could to help them.
And there's one thing, you know, I don't want it on the record, so I'll erase it.
When I went in, I had a little problem with, of course, the standard of living was low.
And they would come, well, they tried to, we had a little kitty set up in the county administered by Bill, the president, Bill.
But that money was, you know, I think the city of College Station put $100 in it.
The county put $100.
Brian put $100 in it.
And this was for indigent people that really weren't the desperate straights to use.
And we had some situations out here in College Station among the blacks that were desperate.
And I tried everything, through the churches and everything, to help all of them that I possibly could.
And in desperation, I set up, and this, of course, was an outgrowth, too, of our meetings, you might say a fun, personal,

in the Baptist church now, with the stipulation, and I added to it, you know, month by month, as I could, with the stipulation that anybody that needs that money, there was one woman that had cancer and had to be used for treatment.
With the stipulation that anybody that needed money could borrow it,

uh from this fund if they could pay it back well i expected to pay them back but if not just forget about it and before i established that fund i had all kinds of problems you know with people coming for me to me for help but once i got that fund put in and in place and got it started and added to it that really fixed it up
And with my heart, I feel good about that, more so in a lot of things.
But I wouldn't want anybody.
Well, that is wonderful.
Yeah.
But I tried to do everything that I could for them.
Well, for everybody.
Because Saturday, you know, I was all over the city on Saturday.
Any complaint, anybody had any, you know, I would say.
Yeah.
Well, before the fire at Lincoln was set, had there been...
had people been discontented among the Negro community because they were frustrated that they wouldn't be in the same school?
That's right.
Is that right?
So it not only occurred in the conversation, it also occurred to me why at the same time they were in the same school.
Oh, yeah.
But it's interesting, you know, knowing the history of London.
That's right.
Who did it and all.
Of course, the record will never know.
I mean, there'll be no record.
When you were on the council, what was the council's feeling or length of feeling about promoting commercial growth?
As I read, it really wasn't in the late 50s, well, not in the 40s, late 50s.
It was in the very early 50s.
It wasn't very much commercial growth.
And then it really picked up after that.
And I was wondering what my college was like.
I don't know how to answer that.
I was just trying to think of the growth.
Actually, we didn't really have much growth until later than that.
You said 50, didn't you?
Yeah.
The only primary growth was
over on the other side of the track.
But if I remember, for example, those paying the highest taxes in the city of College Station, even up through 1962 or so, was Luther Jones.
And Luther was, he had a number of houses that he was renting.
So maybe for that reason he had to pay more taxes.
I was looking at something not too long ago when I saw it fell down.
There wasn't really too much growth during Langford's period.
We had the, you don't remember the Bluetooth ports going in?
No, I don't remember, but I heard of them.
Yeah.
See, they went out of business, and that was a surprise to me.
But that was early on, yeah.
But there was no push to bring in, um, the latest kind of industry here?
No, not, not in, not particularly.
But there was not a need for it?
Well, it was just a small community here.
And, uh, I guess our main concern then was, uh,
fighting, and I don't say fighting, but getting along with Brine people.
In the early years?
Well, during Langford's period.
For example, I don't know whether the records reflect it or not, but if you read between the lines, we got word one night that the city of Brine was going to incorporate
the airport and university land on the first week.
This came from a reliable source.
So we met in an emergency session and incorporated all that land ourselves.
Now that, of course, foreclosed on them taking the initiative.
that is why all university land is within the city of columbus today what year i'd say around 63 but i mean you know this these were little things and the agitator was quite a bit
You know, this community was always different because it was an educational community.
And, well, there were so many things, right?
We were, you know, about seven miles from Bryan.
I mean, it was an old country road that blacked out the road between me and Bryan at that time.
Brine was a fur piece, you know, the town.
And they didn't like a lot of things.
We had our own hardware store in the University Hall.
They made us close in.
And they didn't like the idea of the creamery out there.
They didn't like the idea of, you know, we used to go out and pick berries and, you know, pick three quarts and get one and all this kind of stuff.
They didn't like that.
There were a lot of things that just kept, kept agitating.
You know, our group out here.
Oh yeah, it was during the Lankridge period.
Just little things came up.
And then when I got in, I mentioned to you this matter of the taxes.
And the same thing came up about wiring houses.
Somebody was

filed on and from college station for wiring a house in brian and he had a phd in electrical engineering and but he didn't have his license from brian but brian that wouldn't give anybody in college so that posed another of my problems and i did the same thing as i did with taxes
And within the full space of a day, why, it was all rectified.
But I mean it, you know, just one of these little things.
But then you got to get back and understand some of the early families in Grimes liked to control everything.
You know, that's another part of the thing.
What bank in Grimes liked to do the controlling?
Well...
I think you don't want to talk about it.
Well, you know, a certain thing.
Like to dominate everything in the community.
If anything went on, any elections were held.
It had to be just like they wanted it.
Their candidate had to win.
You know, things like that.
That's part of the political picture that exists.
For example, I was trying to get a nursing home out here.
Well, a nursing home, and it was supposed to be a sort of a retirement village that would be constructed six miles down the road here just outside the city.

It would eventually come into the city, but it would be an ideal thing because they were going to put sort of a clinic with that and had the approval of the then doctor, two doctors in the city of College State.
But Brian got on the ball and stopped him.
How did they stop him?
Through this esteemed senator, Bill Moore.
You know, it's politics.
Which are very complicated.
Oh, yeah.
Well, the bank that you were talking about today, he has on the college station a collection too, the Brian bank?
No, but they wanted to control everything.
They controlled taxis.
They controlled electricians.
See, they didn't have everything.
In other words, you couldn't build without somebody in brine.
You build according to standards out here, but no one could do it except someone from brine.
I mean, wire your house or, you know, do things like this.
So that's not right.
I don't like injustice regardless of where it is.
Well, they have the contractors.
And they did the wiring.
And they're the ones that were authorized to do it.
Not to work in Bryan.
But Bryan people could work either in Bryan or Colorado State.
because we recognize you as being qualified to do it.
But Brian says, well, that's all right, but we're not going to recognize your people because we want to keep fire and we want to keep control.
They wanted to keep the control, that was the key.
Well, did the bank that you were talking about, was it interested in college station officers?
Oh, yeah.
It was interested in controlling whatever went on in Grants County.
Okay, we've talked about it off and on, but I wanted to ask you some questions about your years as mayor.
And you were the first mayor after my first, and here you were starting a period after someone had been off with you for 24 years.
What did you, how did you want to do things differently, or how did you pursue the role of mayor?
Or are they the same?
but there was a change in the city now.
Oh, yeah, well, I think it was reflected in that five-year plan in a way.
You read that over there.
Yes, we did.
You submitted it in your first year, I think.
I don't know whether it was the first year or not.
I just forget now.
But the things that were enumerated there were things that I wanted to see done.
Now, that change in the name that brought all that all over the United States from College Station, you know, malfunction junction and all that kind of stuff, I had to close that down.
But I was really sincere, and I see it still coming up.
You know what I mean.
College Station, I mean, it's still, I wish we had Aggieland
Something else.
A lot of these things were in my mind.
I tried to go through various areas.
We had an explosion on the other side of the track and a former chemical plant over there.
I was interested in that.
I walked the railroad track, I guess about eight miles, and made a report on the track.
It was bad then.
I mean, the nails and the tie and everything else.
They figured out the topography of the land and if there was a spill, where the spill would go.
And, you know, down by the topography of the land and expressed some concern there and what could be done or should be done.
In all of these areas, I just
Now, that plan, that five-year plan, so to speak, I referred that to, if I recall, 100 citizens.
And for their comment, digest, input, criticism, everything else.
And I heard from most of them.
And after I heard, well, then I had a better understanding of things, you know,
Some of them, you know, were very good.
A little thing like the cemetery, you know, I studied that for a little bit about the land.
Did we have enough land?
Would that land furnish us for how many years, you know, 20, 30 years?
What restrictions should we place on it other than those we have right now?
I don't know about the flowers they have right now, but that's something else.
Oh, I gave everybody an opportunity to buy the plots.
The land cost for the plot cost was very, very low.
Way people were coming.
And a lot of people combined were coming out here because of the trucks.
So I gave our people an opportunity to buy lots before we upped the price.
And then appointed people that were really, at that time, very interested in the cemetery.
And I tried to look at each area for safety.
The highway department didn't have too much money.
They had some federal money for signal lights, but
In the area of signal lights, you know, I tried to evaluate it there with others and spoke to Joe Hanover and as many as I could on, well, on each area that went into that five-year report.
But then I knew that I wouldn't be approved when I got the Boyette one.
Oh, didn't you talk about the Boyette section?
Can you name the other ones that were on the council?
Yeah.
And who else were there?
Oh, they varied.
They represented the three wars.
Boynton and this other war, I can think of them all.
I forgot their names.
Some of them, you know, they were on and then another one came on.
Yeah, he's gone.
Yeah.
He went with them.
Yeah.
But that would be the three there.
That's right.
But Rosbam was on last, but there was another fellow on before him.
I mean, they swapped off.
The thing about it, I went to Rossman and sat down in his home and spoke to him about a lot of these things.
And he agreed with me.
He said, you know what I mean, Andy, that's right.
It should be this way.
This should be done.
This should be done.
And I said, well, why then can't you, why won't you support me?
Why the heck?
The people want this.
Why are you denying it to them?
Well, you know, after he's a good friend of mine, and this, that, and the other, and we go to a council meeting, I never could.
I never could change it.
So then from the next council, you know, I could almost dictate who would end.
You know, who do you want as councilman?
From then on, I didn't have any problems at all.
We were talking about your five-year plan.
Was this something that you started on?
Had Mr. Lankford made a list of goals?
No.
This was really mine.
You asked, you know, what was your thinking about the future.
And these are some of the things that came to mind that I haven't looked at, and I haven't talked to you about, and I haven't looked at.
Okay, I also... You looked it over, didn't you?
Yes, I did.
Sure did.
Also, you were the first, and your administration was the first to have annual reports.
Right.
That was part of it.
I felt that we needed to communicate with the public, yes, but what...
The different departments were doing, you know, what we were doing.
Do you know if they still have the papers?
They do not.
They don't?
It terminated after I got out.
Who got these papers?
Well, some papers.
Well, I know the city got those papers now, but a lot of cities still use the news media to get an annual report to the people.
Oh, I see.
The paper that you're reading.
Yeah, they take maybe two or three pages or four pages or something like that.
and give them stewardship for the city.
And I just felt that it was well for us to, you know, let the people know just what was going on with Cleveland City.
Right.
Oh, yeah.
Everybody was on the city's head in those kind of times.
Also, I noticed that you, well, we talked about this, you decided that there should be more committees, is that right?
Yeah.
Yeah, I started with committee council.
There was only a handful of committees?
Well, the only thing is I recall on this planning zone, what kind of things?
And what other ones did you install?
Well, I installed the parks, traffic safety,
There are about six of them.
Oh, well, in my black community.
Oh, yeah, beautification.
All right.
A what?
Sanitary?
I'd have to look it up.
Okay.
But, you know what I mean.
In all these areas...
Well, sanitation, yeah.
Because we had rodent control.
We had several problems when I was mayor.
There was one polio.
And we started collecting mosquitoes and sending them down to Houston for analysis.
I don't know if that's in the record or not.
Well, I started that because horses around here were getting polio.
And polio wasn't, at that time, you know, wasn't really under control.
And I thought this would be a helpful method to, or a step, to control.
But if we knew that the mosquitoes around here had, well, we sprayed, but I mean we could intensify our spray and get,
people more aware of the fact that if you get out at night or, you know what I mean, get bitten by mosquitoes, that there is a chance that you may get polio.
And then there's another, I remember one instance where we had a rat problem.
And that rat problem was primarily on a creek dividing brine and polystation.
And this is where my committee came into play.
Jim Ford was my rodent man.
I picked a dentist, a rodent, veterinarian.
Yeah, it was a sanitary committee, yeah.
And so I called on this committee and picked the rodent man to eliminate the rats

they were coming in the garages you know where the uh well that where that creek area is between the two cities yeah yeah yeah so uh he went over there and he got rid of now we were using stuff nobody nobody he knew what he was doing but he got rid of what he was doing
Is that not allowed?
It's not allowed today.
It's not?
Oh.
But it got rid of them.
Well, it got rid of them.
You could go over there during the daytime, and they were running around in the garages.
It was the kids.
See, these are the things that worried me.
I mean, anybody say anything against College Station, boy, I'd just .
This was my city.
Well, the committee may not be the same today, but they still have a lot of committees.
So apparently, you started a .
Well, I started the committee out in .
But this health committee, I remember the mosquitoes and the rats and something else.
I haven't had time to think about
some of these questions.
Also, I noticed that
You wrote letters to them and memos to their councilmen, just discussing what ought to be done.
I didn't know they still had them done.
I wrote a weekly letter to all the councilmen.
There are some of them.
I don't know if it's complete or not.
Is this something that you get to talk about?
I felt, see, I was in closer touch with what went on in the city on a daily basis.
And I figured that the council should be aware of some of the things.
You know, some of them were short, one page.
It depended on what transpired that week.
And in order to keep them appraised of what went on, well, I wrote these little notes.
Was it something you all did in May or something like that?
No.
It was something you did?
Yes.
Okay.
Also, I had read that you tried to put a city library and city archives together and establish .
Yeah, but that never, that never panned out.
We never had the money.
And this is, uh, I don't know what I was thinking about.
This is Thomas, F.L.
Thomas.
The park is named that way.
And we owe him this Thomas.
He was a great friend of mine.
Well, I could do nothing lying on that side.
But one thing she wanted was the establishment of a library.
And she'd donate all her books.
I think she still has them.
She has them.
She has a wife.
You know, she used to have a radio program for kids daily and weekly and something.
She used to be very active.
